In any of biological-related application, the biosafety evaluation and degradability of nanomaterials are significant to ensure the safety to biological tissues. Compared with conventional nanomaterials, such as metal nanostructures, semiconductor nanoparticles and carbon nanomaterials [64-72], BP-based nanomaterials are fascinating material for biomedical applications benefiting from their inherent biocompatibility. P is an essential element making up ~1% of the total body weight as a bone constituent in the human body [73- 76]. Based on the unique structure unlike graphite, each sheet of BP is not flat and the elemental atoms are connected by weak force. Thus, BP nanoparticles can strongly react with oxygen and water and finally degrade to non-toxic phosphate and phosphonate in the aqueous solution which makes it much better than other traditional two-dimensional materials that could accumulate in the organs [77, 78]. In a study by Shao and co-workers (Fig. 4), the degradability of BPQDs was surveyed [79]. Apparent time-dependent biodegradation behavior of BP nanomaterials was observed in their studies. The biodegradation rate of exfoliated BP under distinct atmospheres (Ar, air and O2, respectively) was further researched by Xie group [46]. Three suspensions under distinct atmospheres were illumi-
nated continuously for about 2 hours. As indicated in the Fig. (5a), the exfoliated BP in oxygen atmosphere shows the fastest degradation rate. The results demonstrate that oxygen is the essential element in photodegradation of BP.
For toxicity study, Chen et al. [80] did the toxicity evaluation on 4T1, HeLa, L929, and A549 cells with various concentrations of BP using the 3-[4,5- dimethylthiazol-2-yl]-2,5-diphenyltetrazolium bromide (MTT) assay. The results demonstrate that no obvious cytotoxicity was observed for all four cell types even at a high concentration up to 200 μg mL-1. Lee et al. [81] also explored the cytotoxicity of BP-nanodots to Hela, COS-7, and CHO-K1 cells through the MTT analysis (Fig. 5b and c). Their results showed that no or little cytotoxic effects of BP-based nanoparticles could be observed for those kinds of cells, unlike pristine graphene with extended cytotoxic responses [82, 83] and this excellent property may benefit from their good degradability.
